default5default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHMIC Inspectiondefault – The Crime Scenedefault&#xa0;default5.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultDuring the visit to Wiltshire Police by HMIC in 2011 
defaultin support of their thematic inspection ‘Cr
defaultime Scene’ 
defaultaround 120 incidents
default were assessed to see if they had been correctly recorded as a crime.
default&#xa0;default5.2
default&#xa0; 
default 
defaultIt was clear that the only issues raised were where an incident that they felt should have been recording as a crime hadn’t been.
default&#xa0;default5.3
default&#xa0; 
defaultI raised directly with
default the inspectors why they had not identified incidents that had been recorded crime where there was credible evidence to the contrary.
default&#xa0;
default5.4
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe view from the lead Inspector (Superintendent Steve Wallace – Hants Police) was that if a victim thought it was a crim
defaulte then it should be recorded as such.  Proportionality would come in the investigative stage following an incident being recorded as a crime.  
default&#xa0;
default5.5
default&#xa0; 
defaultSuperintendent Wallace cited his previous experience as a crime registrar in Hampshire Police.
default&#xa0;default5.6
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe ACPO report
default – Understanding Crime Recording also raises the issue that HMIC and crime registrars interpret the question of ‘when to record’ in this way.
default&#xa0;
default5.7
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe
default view was also shar
defaulted by our force crime registrar.
default 
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default6default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOver recording of crimes.default&#xa0;default6.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultOn becoming Chief Constable 
defaultof Wiltshire Brian Moore set out to make Wiltshire the “Safest in the Country”.  This became interpreted internally to a more measurable ‘lowest rates of violent crime in the country’.
default&#xa0;
default6.2
default&#xa0; 
defaultDuring the summer of 2010, in my role as Performance Manager, I identi
defaultfied that Wiltshire Police had significantly higher rates of 
default‘
defaultno crime
default’
default for less serious assaults than the other ‘top ten forces’ with the lowest violent crime rates.
default&#xa0;
default6.3
default&#xa0; 
defaultAnalysis showed that in
default 
defaultexcess
default of 2
default0
default% of these had been recorded as ‘no crimes’ within f
defaultive days of the initial report.  At the time force procedures were such that the additional verifiable information (AVI) required to achieve a ‘no crime’ decision often needed to be in documentary form e.g. statement. 
default&#xa0;
default6.4
default&#xa0; 
defaultIt became clear to me that for 
defaultthese
default crimes the AVI would have been available following basic and straightforward enquiries.  I further hypothesised there was a high level of probability that AVI 
defaulteither had been or 
defaultcould have been established within the 3x24 hour period allowed by NCRS to ma
defaultke a decision as to whether to record as a crime.  
default&#xa0;
default6.5
default&#xa0; 
defaultI further hypothesised there was a high probability that there were other crimes 
defaultwith information 
defaultwhich, whilst 
defaultit
default would not satisfy the requirement of AVI, would have ‘credible evidence to the contrary’
default.
default&#xa0;
default6.6
default&#xa0; 
defaultOne of the key differences with reported common assaults
default, as compared to other crime types, is
default that in the 
defaultoverwhelming
default majority of cases the ‘offender’ is known
default, and named,
default by the victim.  This provides an opportunity to quickly identify an alternati
defaultve version of events (as there invariably is) and ethically apply the NCRS threshold test
defaults
default e.g.
default do the circumstances amount to a crime in law AND that there 
defaultis 
defaultno
default credible evidence to the contrary.
default&#xa0;
default6.7
default&#xa0; 
defaultAnalysis of a significant sample of common assaults was c
defaultarried out by myself and a temporary Inspector on our team who had extensive experience as a detective
default.
default&#xa0;
default6.8
default&#xa0; 
defaultWe took a deliberately literal inte
defaultrpretation of the words of NCRS specifically around the balance of probabilities that it was more likely than not th
defaultat the incident was as the result of a criminal act and whether there was any other credible evidence.  
default&#xa0;
default6.9
default&#xa0; 
defaultThere does however seem to be a contradiction with NCRS which states it is for the police to determine whether a crime has been committed but states t
defaulthat in most cases the belief by the victim that a crime has occurred is sufficient to justify its recording.
default&#xa0;
default6.10
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOur analysis showed that in around 40% of the cases we examined there was other evidence that gave an alternative version of events that could be 
defaultdeemed credible.  
default&#xa0;
default6.11
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis is not to suggest that 40% had been incorrectly recorded.  What we concluded however was that there was a significant risk that crimes were being re
defaultcorded that shouldn’t have been due to a lack of recognition of credible evidence 
defaultto the contrary.
default  
default&#xa0;
default6.12
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn many cases the incidents occur when only the victim and offender are present and there is an absence of forensic evidence.  This presents the police with a significant dilemma. 
default&#xa0;
default6.13
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTo verify our findings we sought an independent operat
defaultional Detective Sergeant to also make an independent assessment of the same incidents.  The findings of t
defaulthis DS supported our findings.
default&#xa0;
default6.14
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSimilar issues are also raised in the NPIA – Understanding Crime Recording
default 
defaultwhich is available on the College of Policin
defaultg Website.
default&#xa0;
default6.15
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Understanding Crime Recording report encourages ‘greater use of professional judgement in relation to all aspects of the crime recording process and in particular around what constitutes ‘credible evidence to the contrary’ and ‘additional v
defaulterifiable information’.
