defaultImpacts of the over recording of crime.default&#xa0;default7.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultover 
defaultrecording of 
defaultcrime 
defaultcan have significant impacts on individuals 
defaultand police resources.  It can risk public confidence in the police.
default&#xa0;
default7.2
default&#xa0; 
defaultQuite rightly there is an expectation that police will deal with identified suspects expeditiously.  Often the method of ‘dealing with’ suspects of violent crime is to invoke the power of arrest.  
default&#xa0;
default7.3
default&#xa0; 
defaultWithin Wiltshire Police once a violent crime ha
defaultd
default been rec
defaultorded as such and a suspect named and linked to that crime there 
defaultwas
default a performance culture linked to ‘customer satisfaction’ and  ‘detection rates’ which place
defaultd
default insurmountable pressure on officers to make arrests.
default&#xa0;
default7.4
default&#xa0; 
defaultAs a local Joint Branch Board we are 
defaultcurrently supporting an ex-officer who has suffered significant psychological damage as a result of an unnecessary arrest related to a dubious decision making process in relation to an allegation of fraud.  This has had a significant on her life.  Often as
default police officers we forget the impact that an arrest can have
default on individuals
default.  
default&#xa0;
default7.5
default&#xa0; 
defaultWhen incidents are not recorded as crimes there is less pressure
default to make arrests
default.  As a result investigating officers have more scope to use professional judgement
default in the inve
defaultstigation.
default&#xa0;
default7.6
default&#xa0; 
defaultConversely with increased opportunities for use of professional judgement comes an increased risk that crimes that should have been recorded as crimes haven’t
default been
default.
default  Clear strategies need to be in place to mitigate these risks.
default&#xa0;
default7.7
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe culture of 
defaultWiltshire police 
defaulthad a 
defaulttend
defaultency
default 
defaultfor strategic 
defaultfocus 
defaultto be 
defaulton the outcomes of 
defaultthe 
defaultinvestigations 
defaultinto recorded crime 
defaultrather than the quality and integrity of investigations
default into reported incidents
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default7.8
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn respect of recorded crime this
default 
defaultimproved in late 2011 w
defaultith an understanding that victim satisfaction survey results had identified low levels of satisfaction with the quality of the investigations.  
default&#xa0;
default7.9
default&#xa0; 
defaultA plan to improve quality of investigations was implemented and showed positive results.  
defaultThe same focus was n
defaultot given to the investigation of incidents
default. 
default 
default 
default&#xa0;
default7.10
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is
default constant pressure at all levels of management to improve detection rates
default.
default  
default&#xa0;
default7.11
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs Wiltshire’s single point of contact for the National Crime mapping system when it went live I received numerous ‘complaints’ from people about the level of crime in their neighbourhoods.  It became evident that people had concerns that high crime levels
default may affect property prices.  
default&#xa0;
default7.12
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOne of the other concerns that I have is around enhanced vetting.  Where people are named as suspects against recorded crimes there can be a requirement to disclose.
default&#xa0;
default7.13
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn one example I was made aware of related to
default a decision 
defaultfor disclosure that had been referred to the Assistant Chief Constable for a determination.
default&#xa0;
default7.14
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDuring an enhanced CRB check on an individual it became apparent that he was the ‘suspect’ in an allegation of child abuse (physical).  The circumstances were that
default the allegation had been made by his ex-wife some time after they had separated.  The reporting person wished no further action.  The 
defaultreport however 
defaultwas recorded as a crime and the ‘suspect’
default was never approached or advised of the allegation. 
default&#xa0;
default7.15
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe absence of an investigation and the failure to identify any potential evidence to the contrary could have had a significant impact on the job prospects of the accused.  
default&#xa0;
default7.16
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn my view this risks undermining one of the foundations of our criminal justice 
defaultsystem of being ‘innocent until proven guilty.’
